	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Caribbean’s growing relations with emerging nations affect historical EU ties </h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A discussion paper has been published by ECDPM on the implications for Caribbean relations with the EU and the ACP of changing trade relationships in the Caribbean region. The paper notes that globalisation, shifting international trade policy and the changing macro-economics and foreign policies of industrialised nations have positioned the Caribbean as a region of strategic interest in global geopolitics. The moving away of the Caribbean from its historical trade and economic relationship with the EU is evident in new reciprocal trade arrangements and the virtual dissolution of the African, Caribbean and Pacific grouping as a result of the conclusion of regionally based EPAs.</p><p>This has occurred at a time when emerging economies have been pursuing more expansive foreign policy initiatives in order to sustain and consolidate their growing role in international trade.</p><p>The paper notes that these trends have driven the engagement strategies in the Caribbean of emerging economies such as Brazil, China, India and Venezuela. Relations have now moved beyond informal and <i>ad hoc</i>, initiated through the large diaspora, into formal ‘agreements that institutionalise their relations with the Caribbean’. The development cooperation frameworks and engagement strategies of these emerging economies appear to be well matched to the long-standing Caribbean goals of fostering greater south–south cooperation and promoting a collective development agenda, while respecting national sovereignty. This approach is less ‘conditional’ than the approach favoured by the region’s traditional development partners (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/EC-releases-aid-fund-following-sugar-privatisation" target="_blank">EC releases aid fund following sugar privatisation</a>’, September 2010). If global economic conditions continue to favour sustained growth, it is very likely that the Caribbean will remain open to the further development of trade and economic cooperation relations with these non-traditional partners.</p><p>The rapidity with which these relations are evolving has not gone unnoticed and is causing changes in the engagement strategies of traditional partners. The paper observes that although the EU will remain a stable and strategic partner in the Caribbean, the current negotiation of a Joint Caribbean–EU Strategy (JCEUS) is ‘in part informed by the recognition of the EU that its position and influence in the region is being challenged’. The US shares similar concerns, in particular over the growing and strategic entrenchment of Chinese interests. The Caribbean’s new relations appear to be strategically ‘pushed’ by the interests of these emerging players. While benefits can be extracted from such interests, the assessment of the paper is that it would be more prudent for the region to strengthen its own ‘pull’ factor by pursuing a common development agenda that prioritises and strengthens regional integration.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ECDPM, ‘Emerging players in the Caribbean: What implications for the Caribbean, their relations with the EU and ACP?’, by A. Montoute, <i>Discussion Paper</i> No. 116,<i> </i>June 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Download.nsf/0/A75A52BF49807791C12578BD0030A334/$FILE/11-116-emerging%20players.pdf" target="_self">http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Download.nsf/0/A75A52BF498077...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In 2002, the Caribbean region was advised to pursue strategic global repositioning to redefine its relations with traditional partners and to guide its engagement with new and emerging players. It now appears that global reconfiguration, driven by the BRIC economies (particularly Brazil, India and China), is providing the region with an opportunity to embed its development agenda in the new and emerging models that go beyond the traditional trade for development model. South–south cooperation, a long-standing foreign policy of the region, is becoming pivotal to this goal. The agriculture, food and agro-processing industries, which are considered to have yielded only limited successes with traditional trade and economic agreements, are among the sectors being aggressively positioned to benefit from these evolving partnerships, which are fundamentally different in approach and structure. </p><p>Depending on the development need in question, the entry of the BRIC economies is viewed as either an alternative or a complement to relations with traditional partners. Because of this model and the apparent rapid response capacity, BRIC countries are increasingly being approached as an important part of the solution to alleviating short- and medium-term problems in agricultural development. </p><p>For some time now, Caribbean countries have been trying to forge stronger links with the Brazilian Agricultural Research Corporation (Embrapa) for the transfer of knowledge and innovation in areas that range from food production and marketing to small-scale producer cooperatives, associations and family agriculture.</p><p>The growing Chinese investment in the Jamaican sugar sector, alongside the impact of EU sugar sector reforms, is likely to see the Jamaican sugar sector re-evaluate traditional marketing arrangements. This appears to have already taken place in the rice sector, where Guyanese rice exports are expanding more rapidly to regional markets than to the traditional export market in the EU (the EU now takes only 54% of Guyanese rice exports compared to 80% in 1996). </p><p>However, within these evolving trade relationships, Caribbean countries have not discounted the need to maintain strong relations with the EU, particularly linked to addressing the long-term development needs of the sector.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
